Barack Obama to receive Nobel Peace Prize as fourth U.S. president
U.S. President Barack Obama will arrive in Oslo, Norway, for 26 hours to receive the Nobel Peace Prize as the fourth U.S. president in history.
The diploma, medal and cheque for $1.4 million will be given, among other things, for exceptional efforts to strengthen world diplomacy and cooperation between nations.
The White House chief of staff will fly to the Norwegian capital in the morning with his wife, Michelle, and will be busy.
He will first visit the Nobel Institute, where he will meet for the first time with five members of the committee, selected by him in October from 172 people and 33 organizations.
The presidential couple then have a scheduled meeting with Norwegian King Harald V and Queen Sonja.
In the afternoon, the visit will culminate in a ceremony at which Obama will accept the prestigious award.
He will win it as the fourth U.S. president, but only the third to win the prize directly in office.
The White House has already announced that Obama will talk about the Afghan war when accepting the award.
The president does not want to avoid this topic because he realizes that he is taking over the prize as a president who is currently at war in two countries.
He increased the war effort a few days ago by sending more troops to Afghanistan, which he will not forget to highlight any of his critics.
At the ceremony, Obama will also receive a gold medal, diploma and a cheque for ten million Swedish crowns (about 24 million Czech crowns).
He intends to put them on charitable purposes, but he has not yet decided on a particular charity.
The busy schedule will then take the president to a banquet, where, in addition to the Norwegian king and queen, there will also be a prime minister and 250 other invited guests.
From the beginning, Obama was rather restrained in the price.
He said, for example, that he felt that he did not fully deserve it.
He also reiterated several times that it is not just a price for him, but for all those who strive for the same values as him.
Immediately after the announcement, he said it was a "call to action" for him.
