USA: Repetition is the mother of wisdom
It is almost comical with what schoolboy's efforts Barack Obama, the president with the reputation of the smartest, repeats on the Afghan question the strategy of his predecessor, whom he himself considered the dumbest.
When he finally sweated out his long-awaited Afghan doctrine, it turned out that he had copied it through a copycat from Bush's Iraqi script three years ago.
Not only does he use the phrase "as in Iraq" several times in the text, but he did not hesitate to even use the name of Bush's statement of January 2007 as the title of his own declaration: "A New Way Forward."
Three years ago, he criticized Bush’s idea of sending fresh military reinforcements to Iraq plagued by civil war as an “irresponsible and, in its consequences, catastrophic decision.”
But the ensuing months have shown that Bush’s strategy, based on the recommendations of field commanders, was the only possible and highly successful strategy that Iraq is not talked about at all today.
It did not improve Bush's reputation, but objectively left his successor a much more grateful starting situation than might have been expected.
In Afghanistan, Barack Obama hopes a miracle will be repeated.
He was again asked to increase the military contingent by field commanders, especially the commander-in-chief of the Afghan operation, General Stanley McCristal, who even harshly criticized the hesitant shooters in the White House despite the subordination habits.
He asked 40 thousand men to break the situation for the better.
The president hesitated for three months, but he didn't fall for anything better, so at least he tricked the general by 10 thousand soldiers.
He managed to wring out the promise of another 5 thousand from Europe, although he himself originally counted on at least 10.
The most problematic of Obama’s strategy seems to be his intention to start withdrawing troops from Afghanistan in 18 months and to end the process within three years. The entire Obama doctrine raises more questions than it provides answers.
Many doubt that the half-height increase will give the same fruit as the advance in Iraq.
Despite the fratricidal wars of recent years, Iraqi society is relatively well-ordered, its leaders honoring the deal.
The Afghan situation is characterised by the opposite symptom - no one can be relied upon and no agreements are being adhered to.
In these conditions, Afghan security forces are preparing badly, accustomed every day to changing the master according to how it suits them.
Political institutions, even if formally established, will remain only a potemkin village, behind which patriarchal tribal relations will continue to grow.
The balance of the interests of the various ethnic groups is extremely complex given the lack of clarity of the circumstances, which further complicate Pakistani and Iranian influences.
Even the construction of an "action-capable state," which is the minimalist goal of the whole operation, doesn't look very real.
The time horizon of Obama's strategy is striking with his voluntarism.
Over the past eight years, the situation in Afghanistan has only worsened and is now on the brink of an explosion.
To believe that soldiers sent into the tumult of war for the purpose of "early return home" will cause a miracle done here, only a truly romantic soul can be truly romantic, untouched by reality.
From a political point of view, determining the date of withdrawal of troops is a pure irresponsibility, because the Taliban will see this as an indirect granting of American defeat.
The latest NATO summit showed that the willingness of Europeans to participate in combat operations in Afghanistan is coming to a minus.
European politicians do not know and do not want to explain to their constituents how the security of Germany or Italy is related to the war in the foothills of the Hindu.
Another factor capable of radically intervening in the situation is the development of events around Iran.
If the situation continues to deteriorate and the intensified sanctions on the Iranians do not impress, there will be an overwhelming question before the United States whether to try to solve the problem by military force.
It will be necessary to answer it at a time when, according to Obama, America will proceed to a winning withdrawal from Afghanistan.
However, any such solution will also mean a dramatic turnaround in the Afghan situation.
The only patch for Barack Obama is the fact that there are three years left until the presidential election, and therefore there is still plenty of time left to come up with another strategy if this proves to be a total failure.
