Czech discovery: a substance that also works on 'hardy' HIV viruses
A team of Czech and German scientists is testing new compounds that can slow the spread of HIV in the body.
The main advantage of the improved substance is that it also works on viruses that have already gained immunity against drugs.
This fact in some cases outweighs the fact that the compound does not affect the common variant of the virus as strongly as some already available drugs.
AIDS cannot yet be cured.
However, patients can significantly prolong the life of a mixture of drugs that prevent the multiplication of HIV in the body.
However, their use is accompanied by a number of side effects.
In addition, the incomplete suppression of the multiplication of the virus results in the development of so-called resistant viruses, against which drugs are already ineffective.
The work of experts from three institutes of the Academy of Sciences of the Czech Republic, from the University of Technology in Prague and from the University of Heidelberg opens the way to deal with the resistance of the virus.
They have shown that substances called metallocarbons act on the protein responsible for the multiplication of HIV.
Metalcarbons are compounds of boron, hydrogen, carbon and cobalt.
These compounds block the spread of the virus differently than all drugs used today, and therefore can overcome the problem of resistance.
In their work, scientists come up with new ‘enhanced’ compounds prepared based on knowledge of the molecular mechanism of their binding to the viral protein.
Metallocarbons have a unique three-dimensional structure: two multi-walled cages formed by boron, hydrogen and carbon atoms are connected by a metal atom, in this case by cobalt.
A treacherous and resilient virus
HIV protease is a protein of HIV that is essential for the life cycle of the virus.
Without HIV protease caused by the cleavage of HIV, mature infectious viral particles would not have been produced.
When we stop HIV protease, we also stop the spread of the virus in the patient’s body, the researchers explain in a press release published by the Institute of Organic Chemistry and Biochemistry of the Academy of Sciences of the Czech Republic.
In a paper published in the Journal of Medicinal Chemistry, researchers describe a series of compounds in which two pairs of cages (see table) are linked by a short organic chain that is further systematically altered.
A little weaker, but more reliable
The effect of this series of HIV protease substances has been tested in a test tube and also against its resistant (resistant) variants obtained from patients infected with HIV.
