Also, night dreams evaluate Kasten as a form of hallucination.
The hallucination of healthy people does not differ fundamentally from hallucination in acute psychosis.
Compared to schizophrenics, mentally healthy people are able to identify their delusions as unrealistic.
Therefore, Kasten advises its patients to evaluate hallucinations as an extraordinary ability.
Borderline between dream and hallucination
In our world focused too much on the note, the imaginary experience is unfortunately mostly pathologized, says Michael Schmidt-Degenhard, a professor at Heidelberg and chief medical officer of Florence-Nightingale Hospital's Psychiatric and Psychotherapeutic Clinic in Düsseldorf.
Psychosis is a severe, tormented disease, but it also brings positives, creativity - mirage is also an art out of despair.
Schmidt-Degenhard explored the so-called oneiroidal form of experience, a special form of altered consciousness to dream.
Oneiroid states are highly complex, detailed fictional dreams that the affected person considers real and can not even retroactively distinguish them from the waking state.
The oneiroidal state of consciousness arises in extreme situations caused by trauma or disease, for example, patients with polyradicular inflammation who experience motor paralysis in full consciousness.
When a person is threatened by the loss of the world and himself, perhaps by the continuing, complete inability to move, he replaces life-threatening real situations with his own, imaginary world, which is disconnected from reality, says Schmidt-Degenhard.
A type of borderline state between a dream and a hallucination.
Since it is not possible to manage a situation in reality, there will be a change in worlds, but the real situation will become present in the imagination.
An intense form of support for the senses and the transfer of the senses in some unbearable situation that allows us people to self-shape, to move into a loss of consciousness in a moment.
