75% of working mothers have work problems related to motherhood.
Discrimination at work has increased in recent years, especially for women of younger years who intend to have a child.
This is the result of the study 'Fertility and Working Career of Spanish Women', conducted by CSIC in collaboration with the Women's Institute.
The study involved 9,737 women between the ages of 15 and 75, and the results are unambiguous: 75% of working mothers have limited labour market opportunities because of motherhood.
The study highlights that at the beginning of coexistence there are many differences in opinion about the number of children depending on whether they work or not, and also by the type of employment.
Women who do not work outside the home, work part-time or do not have stable jobs, start living with their partner early, previously give birth to their first child and overall have more children.
On the other hand, women with stable employment, especially in the public sector, put off partnership and motherhood, and have fewer offspring.
"Women from 35 to 49 years of age with a stable job have their first child on average 3.7 years old from the start of coexistence with a partner. This figure is 4.1 in the case of women who have devoted most of their lives to achieving their stable employment and have therefore had to postpone the coexistence and arrival of children.
The type of profession also has a strong influence on motherhood, although less influence on the time of coexistence with a partner,” explains Margarita Delgado, who is engaged in research in the CSIC.
Another factor affecting the age of women at the time of marriage the birth of a child is the degree of education.
The research shows that the higher the level of education, the higher the age at which women get married and have their first child.
There are also differences between women of the same generation.
For example, in the age group of 35 to 49, women with primary and higher education gave birth to their first child at the age of 25.1 or. 32.1.
"There is another difference between women depending on their level of education.
Women with basic education are married and give birth to their first child before they find a stable job, while women with secondary or high education proceed the other way to obtain a stable job, to marriage and to the birth of their first child.”
