The auxiliary system for the handbrake is already mandatory equipment.
As in the case of the ABS anti-lock system, it will also be with the stability control of the ESP, the assistant systems of the handbrake, all this will become the mandatory equipment of European cars.
In fact, they are already part of the mandatory equipment of all newly registered passenger cars and light commercial vehicles, while for others, a deadline is set to eliminate the shortage, which is February 2011.
The measure introduced in the EU aims to increase pedestrian protection, working to help prevent many collisions.
The auxiliary system of the handbrake increases the pressure on the brakes in an emergency case, which the system detects after the driver is pressed.
But he can't always sustain that pressure until the end.
According to a study conducted by auto parts manufacturer Bosch, a third of drivers who have an accident did not brake before the collision, and half of them did not fully use the brake strength.
Up to 1,100 accidents
On the contrary, this assistance requires maximum from the braking system, shortening the braking distance of the vehicle.
According to a study carried out in the EU itself, if all vehicles were equipped with this type of equipment, up to 1 100 pedestrian-related fatalities could be avoided.
The reduction in this number will be even more noticeable-according to the calculations would prevent one of four accidents with an impact on people-after the introduction of so-called intelligent handbrake systems.
In this case, the vehicles will be equipped with a system that (using radar or camera) captures obstacles and reports them to the driver, except for light braking.
If the driver reacts, it will help him to increase the pressure on the pedal if needed.
If the driver does not respond, even if the collision cannot be prevented, the device will impress the brake as intensely as possible and reduce the risk of damage to a minimum.
